narrative ever written and a rare example of a single-narrator myth.Now this extraordinary work, composed of thirty-six separate stories, is presented in its entirety for the first time. Beautifully expressed, the narrative constitutes a kind of scripture for a native church, beginning with the creation of the universe out of the void and ending with the establishment in the sixteenth century of present-day villages. Central to the story is the murder/resurrection of a god-man, Siuuhu, who summoned the Pimas and Papagos (Tohono O'odham) as his army of vengeance and brought about the conquest of his murderers, the ancient Hohokam.Donald Bahr extensively annotates the text and supplements it with other Pima-Papago versions of similar stories. Important as a social and historic document, this book adds immeasurably to the growing body of Native American literature and to our knowledge of the development of Pima-Papago culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHohokam culture. 0aPima IndiansvFolklore. 0aPima IndiansxFolklore. 0aTohono O'odham IndiansvFolklore. 0aTohono O'odham IndiansxFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh1 aAllison, William Smith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, Juan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520914568?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520914568/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles